00:38:38.360 --> 00:38:40.160
medical services,
education, et cetera.

00:38:40.160 --> 00:38:43.900
So a lot of the lower
level jobs in China

00:38:43.900 --> 00:38:46.780
are done by people
who are nonresidents

00:38:46.780 --> 00:38:48.340
who are there semi-illegally.

00:38:48.340 --> 00:38:50.320
And sadly, their children
cannot go to school.

00:38:50.320 --> 00:38:51.945
So they have to leave
the children back

00:38:51.945 --> 00:38:54.620
in the countryside be brought
up by their grandparents.

00:38:54.620 --> 00:38:56.715
So this is actually
a massive problem

00:38:56.715 --> 00:38:58.450
that they literally
don't know how

00:38:58.450 --> 00:39:02.710
to solve right now affecting
maybe 100 million people.

00:39:02.710 --> 00:39:05.290
But I don't think
that's necessarily

00:39:05.290 --> 00:39:09.610
going to block innovation per
se because the innovation is

00:39:09.610 --> 00:39:14.410
happening at an upper level, the
scientists and the engineers.

00:39:14.410 --> 00:39:18.880
Secondly, the nature
of China is that it

00:39:18.880 --> 00:39:21.130
is state-driven innovation,
but there are lots

00:39:21.130 --> 00:39:22.700
of private companies as well.

00:39:22.700 --> 00:39:25.810
So many of the most innovative
companies like Alibaba;

00:39:25.810 --> 00:39:28.630
Royole, which I mentioned,
the flexible displays, these

00:39:28.630 --> 00:39:30.490
are strictly private
companies that

00:39:30.490 --> 00:39:34.520
are sort of benefiting from the
Chinese innovation ecosystem.

00:39:34.520 --> 00:39:36.230
And the question I
haven't heard yet,

00:39:36.230 --> 00:39:39.130
but people often
ask me is, well,

00:39:39.130 --> 00:39:41.050
if China is like
controlling people,

00:39:41.050 --> 00:39:43.360
doesn't that stop innovation?

00:39:43.360 --> 00:39:48.240
Well, China doesn't care
so long as you do not

00:39:48.240 --> 00:39:51.090
seek to overthrow
the Communist Party.

00:39:51.090 --> 00:39:53.940
If you're just innovating
and making money,

00:39:53.940 --> 00:39:56.550
they're happy to support you.

00:39:56.550 --> 00:39:58.980
So I really don't necessarily
see that as a problem.

00:39:58.980 --> 00:40:01.180
Or even by the dominance
of a few companies.

00:40:01.180 --> 00:40:02.596
I mean, if you
look at the history

00:40:02.596 --> 00:40:07.500
of the US, many industries
like the automobile industry

00:40:07.500 --> 00:40:12.570
from the 1930s onwards, have
been dominated by two or three

00:40:12.570 --> 00:40:14.050
major companies.

00:40:14.050 --> 00:40:18.390
In fact, in China the problem
isn't too many monopolies,

00:40:18.390 --> 00:40:20.250
it's too many competitors.

00:40:20.250 --> 00:40:22.920
We actually have coined
a phrase in our next book

00:40:22.920 --> 00:40:25.590
with some different co-authors
about swarm innovation.

00:40:25.590 --> 00:40:28.140
We have an article coming
out soon about that.

00:40:28.140 --> 00:40:30.015
There are swarms of
Chinese competitors.

00:40:30.015 --> 00:40:31.890
So there aren't too few
Chinese competitors,

00:40:31.890 --> 00:40:35.252
there are actually
too many of them.

00:40:35.252 --> 00:40:37.710
AUDIENCE: What do you think
are some of the challenges that

00:40:37.710 --> 00:40:40.200
are facing China in
this space and what

00:40:40.200 --> 00:40:43.542
are their leaders
worrying about the most?

00:40:43.542 --> 00:40:45.750
GEORGE S. YIP: Well, if I
just talk about innovation,

00:40:45.750 --> 00:40:49.270
education system is inferior.

00:40:49.270 --> 00:40:51.690
The education system,
top down, traditional.

00:40:51.690 --> 00:40:54.400
Of course, that doesn't
stimulate so much innovation.

00:40:54.400 --> 00:40:57.880
The PhD student will do the work
of the professor, et cetera.

00:40:57.880 --> 00:40:58.960
So they're aware of this.

00:40:58.960 --> 00:41:00.789
And guess what,
they're paying the USA

00:41:00.789 --> 00:41:02.080
to help them solve the problem.

00:41:02.080 --> 00:41:04.500
So Duke University
has a program in China

00:41:04.500 --> 00:41:07.656
to teach Chinese
university lecturers

00:41:07.656 --> 00:41:09.030
how to teach their
students to be

00:41:09.030 --> 00:41:10.544
innovative like the Americans.

00:41:10.544 --> 00:41:12.210
So once again, America
is teaching China

00:41:12.210 --> 00:41:13.960
how to compete with America.

00:41:13.960 --> 00:41:17.030
So that is probably
the biggest problem.

00:41:17.030 --> 00:41:20.160
A secondary problem is the
Chinese language, which also

00:41:20.160 --> 00:41:22.530
affects the education system.

00:41:22.530 --> 00:41:24.030
It's hard for other
people to learn,

00:41:24.030 --> 00:41:27.396
it takes up so much time
and brain space of children.

00:41:27.396 --> 00:41:28.770
I have my own
personal prediction

00:41:28.770 --> 00:41:31.320
that mobile phones are
helping to solve this problem

00:41:31.320 --> 00:41:32.850
because more and
more now, people

00:41:32.850 --> 00:41:35.310
are using the cell
phones to spell for them.

00:41:35.310 --> 00:41:37.680
Actually, older people are
complaining about this.

00:41:37.680 --> 00:41:41.280
I could see this being
outsourced to cell phones.

00:41:41.280 --> 00:41:45.240
AUDIENCE: One area where
the US lags pretty severely

00:41:45.240 --> 00:41:48.350
behind the rest of
the developed world

00:41:48.350 --> 00:41:49.790
is the health care system.

00:41:49.790 --> 00:41:51.950
And you've mentioned
kind of in passing

00:41:51.950 --> 00:41:55.750
kind of the innovations in
medical technology and health

00:41:55.750 --> 00:42:00.560
in China, and I'm wondering
what can the US learn,

00:42:00.560 --> 00:42:03.750
what can the US take from that?

00:42:03.750 --> 00:42:06.000
GEORGE S. YIP: Well, China
doesn't have a great health

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:07.480
care system, either.

00:42:07.480 --> 00:42:10.790
It's surprisingly private.

00:42:10.790 --> 00:42:12.070
People have to pay a lot.

00:42:12.070 --> 00:42:16.880
So the whole state
health care system

00:42:16.880 --> 00:42:23.350
has kind of withered away
post-communist economic system.

00:42:23.350 --> 00:42:27.860
So you can get some services,
but for example, people

00:42:27.860 --> 00:42:33.050
have to pay doctors on the side
to get any serious treatment.

00:42:33.050 --> 00:42:36.050
There's a terrible incentive
in that doctors make money

00:42:36.050 --> 00:42:40.250
by selling medicines, so they
over prescribe their medicines.

00:42:40.250 --> 00:42:43.190
But again, going back
to the technology part,

00:42:43.190 --> 00:42:48.470
they may start to leapfrog
this by digital, et cetera,

00:42:48.470 --> 00:42:50.036
and making it faster.

00:42:50.036 --> 00:42:51.410
I did have one
experience myself.

00:42:51.410 --> 00:42:55.340
I had to go through
a health check.

00:42:55.340 --> 00:42:58.490
And a typical Chinese approach,
it was like a production line.

00:42:58.490 --> 00:43:00.110
Whereas in the
West, I'd have gone

00:43:00.110 --> 00:43:02.810
you know from floor to floor
to the x-ray department,

00:43:02.810 --> 00:43:05.500
to the blood department,
and so on, here it

00:43:05.500 --> 00:43:07.060
was a small building
with a corridor.

00:43:07.060 --> 00:43:11.390
First room, chest x-rays;
second room, blood test;

00:43:11.390 --> 00:43:12.900
third room, eye test.

00:43:12.900 --> 00:43:15.740
So it was like production
line and the whole thing

00:43:15.740 --> 00:43:21.410
cost $100 US, which would
cost you $1,000 in the US.

00:43:21.410 --> 00:43:25.580
AUDIENCE: We all know China
has the largest market

00:43:25.580 --> 00:43:28.970
in the world for many things.

00:43:28.970 --> 00:43:33.770
So many Western companies
tried to enter the market

00:43:33.770 --> 00:43:37.230
without much success.

00:43:37.230 --> 00:43:42.720
What's your view on the top
reasons why Western companies

00:43:42.720 --> 00:43:44.982
often fail in the market?

00:43:44.982 --> 00:43:46.190
GEORGE S. YIP: Good question.

00:43:46.190 --> 00:43:49.670
But to be fair, many
companies have also succeeded.

00:43:49.670 --> 00:43:52.520
So reasons for failure.

00:43:52.520 --> 00:43:55.797
If you go into a
sector where China

00:43:55.797 --> 00:43:57.505
is trying to develop
its own competitors,

00:43:57.505 --> 00:44:01.100
they will make life
very difficult for you.

00:44:01.100 --> 00:44:03.380
They have hidden regulations
they can pull out

00:44:03.380 --> 00:44:05.570
to make it difficult for you.

00:44:05.570 --> 00:44:07.610
So long as you are
contributing something

00:44:07.610 --> 00:44:10.580
that China doesn't have, such
as the Western auto companies

00:44:10.580 --> 00:44:14.600
over the last 30 years,
they're happy to welcome you.

00:44:14.600 --> 00:44:16.640
I mean, I teach
international business.

00:44:16.640 --> 00:44:17.640
It's the same principle.

00:44:17.640 --> 00:44:19.700
You've got to bring
something to the country

00:44:19.700 --> 00:44:20.760
that they don't have.

00:44:20.760 --> 00:44:25.010
So if you have that, then
they will welcome you and not

00:44:25.010 --> 00:44:31.310
make life too difficult.
Then partners--

00:44:31.310 --> 00:44:33.430
for a long time, you
needed a Chinese partner.

00:44:33.430 --> 00:44:37.070
Some were good
partners, some were bad.

00:44:37.070 --> 00:44:41.420
There's a Chinese saying,
[SPEAKING MANDARIN],, same bed,

00:44:41.420 --> 00:44:42.930
different dreams.

00:44:42.930 --> 00:44:46.690
So sometimes the partner was
a nightmare, so to speak,

00:44:46.690 --> 00:44:48.060
following that analogy.

00:44:48.060 --> 00:44:50.240
So that's a reason
why it could go wrong.

00:44:50.240 --> 00:44:52.445
But really, I think
Google's case,

00:44:52.445 --> 00:44:56.690
you actually came right up
against a central policy

00:44:56.690 --> 00:44:59.630
of the government, which
is the privacy issue,

00:44:59.630 --> 00:45:02.510
and that's why you've
been banned from China.

00:45:02.510 --> 00:45:07.960
Plus secondarily, other
companies like eBay--

00:45:07.960 --> 00:45:14.360
the privacy issue-- they wanted
to protect their emerging

00:45:14.360 --> 00:45:15.450
companies.

00:45:15.450 --> 00:45:15.950
That's why.

00:45:15.950 --> 00:45:17.930
So there are still
opportunities,

00:45:17.930 --> 00:45:20.720
but not in areas like that.

00:45:20.720 --> 00:45:24.500
AUDIENCE: So one thing that
I've noticed about competition

00:45:24.500 --> 00:45:27.740
in China is that it's
a very free-wheeling

00:45:27.740 --> 00:45:29.760
from of competition.

00:45:29.760 --> 00:45:33.530
If you have an idea, there
will be a million competitors

00:45:33.530 --> 00:45:37.340
doing the same thing,
maybe better, maybe not.

00:45:37.340 --> 00:45:41.600
That's a very hard situation
for external companies

00:45:41.600 --> 00:45:43.670
because here in the
US, for example, there

00:45:43.670 --> 00:45:52.610
is a strong law field of
patents and IT protection.

00:45:52.610 --> 00:45:57.170
So how can anyone think of
getting to the market in China

00:45:57.170 --> 00:46:00.410
in such a situation where there
is a feeling that everything

00:46:00.410 --> 00:46:01.789
will be stolen?

00:46:01.789 --> 00:46:02.580
GEORGE S. YIP: Yes.

00:46:02.580 --> 00:46:05.420
Actually, what Western companies
are doing more and more

00:46:05.420 --> 00:46:06.950
is that instead of
selling products,

00:46:06.950 --> 00:46:10.770
they're now selling
business models.

00:46:10.770 --> 00:46:13.970
So if you're going to embed the
product in a business system,

00:46:13.970 --> 00:46:19.370
that is much harder
to imitate against.

00:46:19.370 --> 00:46:24.140
So selling the service based
on the product, rather than

00:46:24.140 --> 00:46:27.920
the product itself
or rapidly innovating

00:46:27.920 --> 00:46:33.854
to keep ahead of the imitators
or having superior technology.

00:46:33.854 --> 00:46:36.020
There are ways to protect
your intellectual property

00:46:36.020 --> 00:46:39.740
so that it can't
be fully imitated.

00:46:39.740 --> 00:46:41.900
Interestingly,
the auto companies

00:46:41.900 --> 00:46:44.390
are still ahead in China.

00:46:44.390 --> 00:46:49.630
This may be a good item
to finish with, actually.

00:46:49.630 --> 00:46:52.250
I was told by one of the
German automotive companies,

00:46:52.250 --> 00:46:54.410
they said, the reason
we're still ahead

00:46:54.410 --> 00:46:59.390
is that in the West, the
auto engineers grew up

00:46:59.390 --> 00:47:03.440
being taken to repair
garages by their father

00:47:03.440 --> 00:47:04.640
or their grandfather.

00:47:04.640 --> 00:47:07.700
So they've had this
since childhood,

00:47:07.700 --> 00:47:09.110
these automotive engineers.

00:47:09.110 --> 00:47:12.210
In China, the automotive
engineers are first generation.

00:47:12.210 --> 00:47:14.390
They don't have this
deep background.

00:47:14.390 --> 00:47:17.240
And cars are this very
complex combination

00:47:17.240 --> 00:47:21.620
of being a consumer product
and being a highly engineered

00:47:21.620 --> 00:47:22.460
technical product.

00:47:22.460 --> 00:47:25.010
So actually, they're going to
have more difficulty in cars

00:47:25.010 --> 00:47:29.660
than they have, say, in
commercial jet aircraft.

00:47:29.660 --> 00:47:31.310
And in fact,
interestingly in cars,

00:47:31.310 --> 00:47:34.940
they don't particularly want
the ultimate driving machine,

00:47:34.940 --> 00:47:37.940
like a BMW; they want the
ultimate mobile living room

00:47:37.940 --> 00:47:43.230
because that's a different
kind of experience

00:47:43.230 --> 00:47:45.780
that they want in China.

00:47:45.780 --> 00:47:49.740
There's a great story about
BMW, which is that in China--

00:47:49.740 --> 00:47:51.450
this will be my last comment--

00:47:51.450 --> 00:47:53.820
there was a dating
TV program in China,

00:47:53.820 --> 00:47:56.640
just to show you
again Chinese culture.

00:47:56.640 --> 00:47:58.410
And a young woman
on the TV program

00:47:58.410 --> 00:48:01.500
was asked by a
young man, he said,

00:48:01.500 --> 00:48:03.840
I'm not very rich so would
you go on a date with me

00:48:03.840 --> 00:48:06.270
just on a bicycle?

00:48:06.270 --> 00:48:08.790
And she rejected
him and said, I'd

00:48:08.790 --> 00:48:14.230
rather cry in the back of a BMW
than smile on top of a bicycle.

00:48:14.230 --> 00:48:15.660
So that's Chinese culture.

00:48:15.660 --> 00:48:17.070
Thank you very much.

00:48:17.070 --> 00:48:19.820
[APPLAUSE]

